Notes l have been made as short as is consistent with perspicuity: unless the contrary is expressly stated or implied, the word or words which appear first in the note are those of our text ; thus ‘genitabilis perticalis etc! signifies that genitabilis is the right reading and is found in A and B and the other chief authorities, but genitalia is mentioned for the reasons given. Again ‘281 qaam Lech. torquem. pared J unt’ means that Lachmann first gave the correct reading qiaam instead of quem which is the read- ing of A and B and other mss as well as editions before the J untine cf 1512 which prints quod, the reading generally followed by the old editors. Of course if -any one before Lachmann had read paam, he, not Lachmann, would have been cited for it. ‘Ed' means the present editor. Let it always be remembered that the corrupt reading, cited in a note, is 'that which appears in A and B, unless the contrary is expressly stated.
